WEBVTT

00:12.400 --> 00:24.374
He can find a fire before it starts to flame.

00:24.755 --> 00:26.457
That's why they call him Smokey.

00:26.497 --> 00:28.219
That was how he got his name.

00:28.739 --> 00:29.560
Hi there, friends.

00:29.700 --> 00:30.702
I'm Billy Johnson.

00:30.742 --> 00:32.584
You're singing with me.

00:32.604 --> 00:34.907
Glad you could come this way up a trail again today.

00:35.447 --> 00:39.572
So how about having a seat beside me here on the log under the old pine trees?

00:40.497 --> 00:43.387
Mighty pretty out here in the forest, isn't it?

00:43.407 --> 00:47.140
That's cause we kept fires from running wild around here.

00:47.160 --> 00:52.819
You know, we thought you might enjoy taking time out again today for a few moments of song and storytelling.

00:53.322 --> 00:57.227
Of course, when I say we, I'm including those fellas just across the trail.

00:57.387 --> 00:58.488
Sons of the Pioneers.

00:58.809 --> 01:00.891
They've been waiting for you to come up the trail, too.

01:01.492 --> 01:05.016
Now that you're here, let's start off this little outdoor get-together of ours.

01:05.056 --> 01:08.681
So just relax and let's hear some mighty fine singing, huh?

01:11.284 --> 01:15.229
Hold him down, burn his hide.

01:15.209 --> 01:21.837
There's extra pay for every day, so hold that critter down, burn his high, hold him down.

01:22.719 --> 01:26.684
It's round-up time and the weather's fine and the strays must all be branded.

01:27.044 --> 01:30.989
The irons try and the gogies try, but the old man has commanded.

01:31.009 --> 01:38.719
So all day long I sing this song, hold that critter down, hold him down, burn his high.

01:39.121 --> 01:45.771
There's extra pay for every day, so hold that critter down, burn his hide, holding down.

01:46.572 --> 01:50.317
I'll head for town when the boss comes round with the back pay that he owes me.

01:50.598 --> 01:54.423
Get drunk to sin with my old pal Jim and land where the bouncer throws me.

01:54.704 --> 02:02.395
Then bet him ten he can't do it again, so hold that critter down, holding down, burn his hide.

02:02.797 --> 02:09.446
There's extra pay for every day, so hold that critter down, burn his hide, hold him down.

02:10.227 --> 02:14.192
I'll be back next day with ten minutes' pay left from the check that I drew.

02:14.452 --> 02:18.658
The boss says, son, you're a son of a gun, but I wish that I was like you.

02:18.678 --> 02:22.142
So I'll burn hair for next month's hair and hold that critter down.

02:22.342 --> 02:25.707
Hold him down, burn his hide.

02:26.588 --> 02:32.736
There's extra pay for every day, so hold that critter down, burn his hide, hold him down.

02:33.982 --> 02:44.272
Hold that critter down.

02:44.292 --> 02:49.336
The boys roll that song just about as fast as a fire runs wild through the forest or woods.

02:50.357 --> 02:53.580
Now there's one critter we all ought to lend a hand and hold him down.

02:54.261 --> 02:56.183
Wildfire.

02:56.203 --> 03:00.787
Someone once said, to stage a forest fire you need only a few things.

03:01.348 --> 03:01.828
A forest,

03:02.467 --> 03:09.434
the right atmospheric conditions, and a spark, either from a lightning bolt or a match in the hands of a fool or a knave.

03:10.355 --> 03:11.376
The formula is simple.

03:12.116 --> 03:17.021
The wonder is that we do not have more and bigger fires.

03:17.041 --> 03:28.212
Well, sir, when you consider we still have in the neighborhood of 190,000 forest and wood fires in this country every year, I think you'll agree that's too many.

03:28.232 --> 03:32.136
And whether they're big or small, the damage they do to our timber resources

03:33.078 --> 03:34.620
Well, sir, it's a crying shame.

03:35.501 --> 03:44.733
Because when trees burn, it's not only lumber that goes up in smoke, it's part of the very strength and security of our nation.

03:44.753 --> 03:53.104
When these trees burn, it's the same as burning up money and jobs, and the very foundation of homes and communities.

03:53.124 --> 04:02.697
I want to tell you some more about this, but I see the sons of the pioneers have their hearts set on the beauty of Oklahoma, the state of rolling plains and heavily wooded mountains.

04:03.183 --> 04:03.984
Go ahead, boys.

04:11.618 --> 04:22.677
The everlasting hills of Oklahoma They hold a million treasures to be found

04:26.538 --> 04:51.027
Golden grain on hills of green Wave to valleys, cool and clean Too bad some foes have never teemed The everlasting hills of Oklahoma

04:58.955 --> 05:19.073
The everlasting tales of Oklahoma Are told in clouded statues in the sky Pioneers who long have gone

05:19.306 --> 05:38.175
Their wagon wheels still rumble on when thunder feels and falls upon the everlasting hills of Oklahoma.

05:46.627 --> 05:59.567
The everlasting fame of Oklahoma will live in names of men she claims her own.

06:00.728 --> 06:13.748
Some were right and some were wrong in history's pages, frozen songs.

06:13.947 --> 06:30.488
Oh, hail them now, for they all belong to the everlasting hymn of all.

06:44.474 --> 06:47.919
Well, sir, I'm sure the folks in Oklahoma are mighty proud of that, too.

06:49.061 --> 06:53.168
You know, friends, it really doesn't matter who you are or where you live.

06:53.849 --> 06:57.815
When trees burn, it affects you in one way or another.

06:57.835 --> 07:05.026
Supposing you're a farmer in Kansas or a railroad worker in Seattle or a housewife in Brooklyn.

07:05.047 --> 07:09.514
What does a forest fire burning, say, in Oregon or Mississippi have to do with you?

07:10.435 --> 07:12.338
The answer, my friend, is plenty.

07:13.212 --> 07:14.774
Just think about your own home.

07:14.794 --> 07:16.296
You're mighty proud of it, I know.

07:16.896 --> 07:21.322
And you've spent a lot of money to make it attractive and livable.

07:21.342 --> 07:24.105
But what's helped to make it so?

07:24.125 --> 07:26.869
Wood in all its forms.

07:26.889 --> 07:32.535
Wood from the very forests, perhaps, that are blazing in Oregon or Mississippi.

07:32.556 --> 07:34.478
Oh, we're all in this, all right.

07:34.498 --> 07:35.719
Every one of us.

07:35.739 --> 07:37.882
Whoever we are, wherever we live.

07:38.943 --> 07:42.848
Whether it's in Colorado or Michigan or in Virginia...

07:43.216 --> 08:12.227
