08:12.629 --> 08:16.114
On the trail of the lonesome pine.

08:16.154 --> 08:21.021
Oh, Jew, like the mountains, I'm blue.

08:21.742 --> 08:27.471
Like the pine, I am lonesome for you.

08:27.491 --> 08:30.355
In the blue rich mountains of Virginia.

08:31.476 --> 08:37.565
On the trail of the lonesome pine.

08:37.585 --> 08:40.189
You know, talking about pine trees in Virginia...

08:40.422 --> 08:44.025
All through the south and pretty much everywhere the trees grow.

08:44.726 --> 08:47.669
Do you know what suffers most when the forest or woods burns?

08:48.649 --> 08:53.013
It's the little trees just getting started in life.

08:53.033 --> 08:56.076
Next time you're out in the woods, search out those little fellas.

08:56.637 --> 08:57.678
Seedlings, we call them.

08:58.498 --> 09:01.861
You'll find them hidden in the grass if you look real close.

09:01.881 --> 09:08.067
Now those are the little trees that will grow into our future supply of timber if they're just given the chance.

09:08.772 --> 09:11.636
You see, it doesn't take a big fire to kill those little trees.

09:12.597 --> 09:20.909
The ground fires of the east and south, usually not very dramatic fires, do terrible damage to the seedlings.

09:20.929 --> 09:26.737
Why, it picks them off as clean as you do a platter of tender southern fried chicken.

09:26.757 --> 09:35.890
But seriously, friends, forest and woods fires, no matter how big or how small they are, give our timber resources an awful beat.

09:35.910 --> 09:38.053
We've just got to keep them from getting started.

09:38.725 --> 09:39.806
Don't you agree, Lloyd?

09:40.166 --> 09:42.269
We've seen those things, Billy, close up.

09:42.889 --> 09:47.013
We've had a full dose of fighting forest fires, the boys and myself.

09:47.574 --> 09:50.837
And if we never have to fight another one, it'll be too soon.

09:51.718 --> 10:04.851
You know, if folks could just realize the sweat and back-breaking work and heartbreak, too, that goes with forest fire fighting, I'm sure they'd be careful with fire every time they use it outdoors.

10:05.607 --> 10:26.460
If they had to walk through a burned forest and see for themselves the awful damage that wildfire does, well, let's sing a song, boys.

10:26.480 --> 10:31.648
Oh, sun goes down, work's all done.

10:31.966 --> 10:35.371
Evens here at last.

10:35.812 --> 10:39.738
Moon comes up behind the hills I love.

10:40.519 --> 10:46.367
And I'm ridin' home.

10:47.369 --> 10:51.936
